yers]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Super League Greece players]]\n[[Category:Liga I players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Greece]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Romania]]\n[[Category:Armenian expatriate sportspeople in Greece]]\n[[Category:Armenian expatriate sportspeople in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Armenian expatriate sportspeople in Romania]]\n[[Category:Twin sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of Romania]]\n[[Category:Romanian people of Armenian descent]]\n", "name_user": "Mihaitalazarica", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBuftea", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arman_Karamyan"}
{"title_page": "1883 in Australia", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=January 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2010}}\n{{Year in Australia|1883}}\nThe following lists events that happened during '''1883 in Australia'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n\n=== Governors===\n[[Governors of the Australian states|Governors of the Australian colonies]]:\n* [[Governors of New South Wales|Governor of New South Wales]] \u2013 [[Augustus Loftus|Lord Augustus Loftus]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/web/common.nsf/key/resourcesSystemTheGovernorofNewSouthWales |title=The Governor of NSW |accessdate=22 February 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128084410/http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/web/common.nsf/key/resourcesSystemTheGovernorofNewSouthWales |archivedate=28 January 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Governors of Queensland|Governor of Queensland]] \u2013 [[Arthur Kennedy (governor)|Sir Arthur Edward Kennedy GCMG CB]]/[[Anthony Musgrave|Sir Anthony Musgrave GCMG]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govhouse.qld.gov.au/the_governor/pastgovernors.aspx|title=Governors of Queensland|accessdate=22 February 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305043626/http://www.govhouse.qld.gov.au/the_governor/pastgovernors.aspx|archivedate=5 March 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Governors of South Australia|Governor of South Australia]] \u2013 [[William Jervois|Sir William Jervois]] then [[William Cleaver Francis Robinson|Sir William Robinson]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.governor.sa.gov.au/index.php?m=previous-governors|title=Previous Governors of South Australia|accessdate=22 February 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Governors of Tasmania|Governor of Tasmania]] \u2013 [[George Strahan (colonialist)|Major Sir George Strahan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.tas.gov.au/tpl/DataSheets/Governors_Table.htm|title=Governors of Tasmania|accessdate=22 February 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Governors of Victoria|Governor of Victoria]] \u2013 [[George Phipps, 2nd Marquess of Normanby]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/gov.html|title=Governors of Victoria, 1855 \u2013 Current|accessdate=22 February 2010|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20091002003453/http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/gov.html |archivedate = 2 October 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Premiers===\n[[Premiers of the Australian states|Premiers of the Australian colonies]]:\n* [[Premiers of New South Wales|Premier of New South Wales]] \u2013 [[Henry Parkes|Sir Henry Parkes]] until 5 January then [[Alexander Stuart (Australian politician)|Alexander Stuart]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/web/common.nsf/key/ArchivesLegislativeAssemblyPremiersofNewSouthWales1856todate|title=Premiers of NSW, 1856 to date|accessdate=22 February 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100205075634/http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/web/common.nsf/key/ArchivesLegislativeAssemblyPremiersofNewSouthWales1856todate| archivedate= 5 February 2010 | url-status= dead}}</ref>\n* [[Premiers of Queensland|Premier of Queensland]] \u2013 [[Thomas McIlwraith]] until 13 November then [[Samuel Griffith]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/view/historical/records1860.asp?SubArea=officeHolders|title=Records of Members and Office Holders since 1860|accessdate=22 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090711215723/http://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/view/historical/records1860.asp?SubArea=officeHolders|archive-date=11 July 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Premiers of South Australia|Premier of South Australia]] \u2013 [[John Cox Bray]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.sa.gov.au/Members/FormerMembers/Past+Premiers/Past+Premiers.htm |title=Past Premiers |accessdate=22 February 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091112062449/http://www.parliament.sa.gov.au/Members/FormerMembers/Past%2BPremiers/Past%2BPremiers.htm |archivedate=12 November 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Premiers of Tasmania|Premier of Tasmania]] \u2013 [[William Giblin]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.tas.gov.au/tpl/DataSheets/Premiers_Table.htm|title=Premiers of Tasmania|accessdate=22 February 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100227004414/http://www.parliament.tas.gov.au/tpl/DataSheets/Premiers_Table.htm| archivedate= 27 February 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[Premiers of Victoria|Premier of Victoria]] \u2013 [[Bryan O'Loghlen]] until 8 March then [[James Service]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/minis.html|title=Victorian Premiers Since Responsible Government, 1855 \u2013 Current|accessdate=22 February 2010|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20091002005816/http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/minis.html |archivedate = 2 October 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n* The [[Boag's Brewery|J. Boag & Son]] brewery is established in [[Launceston, Tasmania]].\n* 12 June \u2013 The first [[Australasia]]n headquarters of the [[Salvation Army]] opened in Melbourne.\n* 14 June \u2013 A rail service between [[Sydney]] and [[Melbourne]] commences when the NSW and Victorian rail systems are joined at [[Albury, New South Wales|Albury]].\n* 1 October \u2013 [[Sydney Boys High School]] is founded in [[Sydney, New South Wales]]. It is the first boys public school in Australia.\n* 26 November \u2013 An Australasian Inter-Colonial Conference is held in Sydney. [[Federation of Australia|Federation]] and annexation of surrounding islands are discussed by the Australian colonies, [[New Zealand]] and [[Fiji]].\n\n==Exploration and settlement==\n* Boundary rider Charles Rath discovers the Line of Lode, a massive [[silver]] deposit near the town of [[Broken Hill, New South Wales]].\n\n<!--\n==Science and technology==\n-->\n\n==Arts and literature==\n{{main|1883 in Australian literature}}\n\n==Sport==\n\n* 30 January \u2013 [[English cricket team|England]] defeats [[Australian cricket team|Australia]] 2\u20131 in the [[History of Test cricket (to 1883)#Bligh reclaims the Ashes 1882.2F3|1882\u201383 Test cricket series]], reclaiming \"[[The Ashes]]\" of English cricket.\n*November \u2013 ''Martini-Henry'' wins the [[Melbourne Cup]]\n*2 November \u2013The Northern Rugby Union (later renamed [[Queensland Rugby Union]]) is formed at a meeting in [[Brisbane, Queensland|Brisbane]]\n*[[Petersham RUFC|Petersham Rugby Union Football Club]] formed in Sydney NSW\n\n==Births==\n* 12 April \u2013 [[Dally Messenger]], rugby footballer (died 1959)<ref>{{Australian Dictionary of Biography|last=Cunneen|first=Chris|year=1986|id=A100475b|title=Messenger, Herbert Henry (Dally)  (1883\u20131959) |accessdate=22 February 2010}}</ref>\n* 15 April \u2013 [[Stanley Bruce]] (died 1967), 8th [[Prime Minister of Australia]]<ref>{{Australian Dictionary of Biography|last=Radi|first=Heather|year=1979|id=A070460b|title= Bruce, Stanley Melbourne (1883\u20131967)|accessdate=22 February 2010}}</ref>\n* 30 May \u2013 [[Sandy Pearce]] (died 1930), rugby league footballer and boxer<ref>{{Australian Dictionary of Biography|last=Corcoran|first=Kristine|year=1988|id=A110186b|title=Pearce, Sidney Charles (Sandy)  (1883\u20131930)|accessdate=22 February 2010}}</ref>\n* 1 July \u2013 [[Micky Dore]] (died 1910), rugby league footballer\n* 1 September \u2013 [[Robert Graves (rugby)|Robert Graves]] (died 1958), rugby footballer\n* 12 December \u2013 [[William Baylebridge]] (died 1943), poet and short story writer<ref>{{Australian Dictionary of Biography|last=Bonnin|first=Nancy|year=1979|id=A070217b|title=Baylebridge, William  (1883\u20131942) |accessdate=22 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Deaths==\n* 5 January \u2013 [[Charles Tompson]] (born 1806), poet\n* 18 August \u2013 [[Roger William Bede Vaughan]] (born 1834), [[Catholic Bishops and Archbishops of Sydney|Archbishop of Sydney]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Australia}}\n{{Oceania topic|1883 in|countries_only=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1883 in Australia}}\n[[Category:1883 by country|Australia]]\n[[Category:1883 in Australia| ]]\n[[Category:Years of the 19th century in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=January 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2010}}\n{{Year in Australia|1883}}\nThe following lists events that happened during '''1883 in Australia'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n\n=== Governors===\n[[Governors of the Australian states|Governors of the Australian colonies]]:\n* [[Governors of New South Wales|Governor of New South Wales]] \u2013 [[Augustus Loftus|Lord Augustus Loftus]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/web/common.nsf/key/resourcesSystemTheGovernorofNewSouthWales |title=The Governor of NSW |accessdate=22 February 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128084410/http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/web/common.nsf/key/resourcesSystemTheGovernorofNewSouthWales |archivedate=28 January 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Governors of Queensland|Governor of Queensland]] \u2013 [[Arthur Kennedy (governor)|Sir Arthur Edward Kennedy GCMG CB]]/[[Anthony Musgrave|Sir Anthony Musgrave GCMG]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govhouse.qld.gov.au/the_governor/pastgovernors.aspx|title=Governors of Queensland|accessdate=22 February 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305043626/http://www.govhouse.qld.gov.au/the_governor/pastgovernors.aspx|archivedate=5 March 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Governors of South Australia|Governor of South Australia]] \u2013 [[William Jervois|Sir William Jervois]] then [[William Cleaver Francis Robinson|Sir William Robinson]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.governor.sa.gov.au/index.php?m=previous-governors|title=Previous Governors of South Australia|accessdate=22 February 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Governors of Tasmania|Governor of Tasmania]] \u2013 [[George Strahan (colonialist)|Major Sir George Strahan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.tas.gov.au/tpl/DataSheets/Governors_Table.htm|title=Governors of Tasmania|accessdate=22 February 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Governors of Victoria|Governor of Victoria]] \u2013 [[George Phipps, 2nd Marquess of Normanby]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/gov.html|title=Governors of Victoria, 1855 \u2013 Current|accessdate=22 February 2010|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20091002003453/http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/gov.html |archivedate = 2 October 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Premiers===\n[[Premiers of the Australian states|Premiers of the Australian colonies]]:\n* [[Premiers of New South Wales|Premier of New South Wales]] \u2013 [[Henry Parkes|Sir Henry Parkes]] until 5 January then [[Alexander Stuart (Australian politician)|Alexander Stuart]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/web/common.nsf/key/ArchivesLegislativeAssemblyPremiersofNewSouthWales1856todate|title=Premiers of NSW, 1856 to date|accessdate=22 February 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100205075634/http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/web/common.nsf/key/ArchivesLegislativeAssemblyPremiersofNewSouthWales1856todate| archivedate= 5 February 2010 | url-status= dead}}</ref>\n* [[Premiers of Queensland|Premier of Queensland]] \u2013 [[Thomas McIlwraith]] until 13 November then [[Samuel Griffith]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/view/historical/records1860.asp?SubArea=officeHolders|title=Records of Members and Office Holders since 1860|accessdate=22 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090711215723/http://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/view/historical/records1860.asp?SubArea=officeHolders|archive-date=11 July 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Premiers of South Australia|Premier of South Australia]] \u2013 [[John Cox Bray]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.sa.gov.au/Members/FormerMembers/Past+Premiers/Past+Premiers.htm |title=Past Premiers |accessdate=22 February 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091112062449/http://www.parliament.sa.go